a StormBag box at home.

11:16.476 --> 11:19.012
You know where I got mad at
on that deal, Lori?

11:19.012 --> 11:20.513
That little
cute idea you had.

11:20.513 --> 11:22.982
The little baby bags?
I hated that you
came out with that idea.

11:22.982 --> 11:24.150
I know.
You got me on that one.

11:24.150 --> 11:25.485
And even the little mini bag
you can sell

11:25.485 --> 11:27.520
for $5.95 or $9.95.
Eh, nobody's listening
to you anymore.

11:27.520 --> 11:29.188
Mark, she didn't even
need you in that deal.

11:29.188 --> 11:31.858
[ Laughter ]

11:33.126 --> 11:34.227
Narrator: In Season 6,

11:34.227 --> 11:36.162
we watch David Heath
and Randy Goldberg

11:36.162 --> 11:37.363
make a deal with Daymond John

11:37.363 --> 11:40.133
for their sock company
with a mission -- Bombas.

11:40.133 --> 11:42.302
Heath: We learned that
socks are the number one

11:42.302 --> 11:44.404
most requested clothing item
at homeless shelters.

11:44.404 --> 11:47.273
So for every pair of socks
we sell, we donate a pair.

11:47.273 --> 11:49.309
Let's see what
they're up to now.

11:49.309 --> 11:50.476
We definitely wanted
to be one

11:50.476 --> 11:52.545
of the most successful
companies on "Shark Tank,"

11:52.545 --> 11:54.847
but I don't think we ever
thought it would come true.

11:54.847 --> 11:55.582
No chance.

11:55.582 --> 11:59.419
Our total sales in our first
year of business was $900,000.

11:59.419 --> 12:01.120
And in our fifth year
of business,

12:01.120 --> 12:03.556
we were at
$225 million.

12:03.556 --> 12:06.125
And today,
in our 10th year of business,

12:06.125 --> 12:08.695
we have done over
$1 billion in sales.

12:08.695 --> 12:12.098
And that makes us the first
billion-dollar company

12:12.098 --> 12:13.299
to get a deal
in the Tank.

12:13.299 --> 12:15.368
We now have
186 employees.

12:15.368 --> 12:17.503
We manufacture in
15 different facilities

12:17.503 --> 12:19.372
across eight
different countries.

12:19.372 --> 12:22.208
We founded Bombas with a mission
to help those in need.

12:22.208 --> 12:24.577
One item purchased
equals one item donated.

12:24.577 --> 12:27.013
And while achieving
over $1 billion

12:27.013 --> 12:28.348
is an important milestone,

12:28.348 --> 12:30.416
an even more important
milestone for us

12:30.416 --> 12:34.220
is donating over 100 million
items to those in need.

12:34.220 --> 12:36.122
Why do people love
Bombas so much?

12:36.122 --> 12:37.290
Amazing product.

12:37.290 --> 12:38.458
Amazing story.

12:38.458 --> 12:42.495
Over $1 billion. It shows
that people want to give.

12:42.495 --> 12:44.530
Every time I bought this,
I cleaned up the ocean.

12:44.530 --> 12:46.432
Every time I bought this,
I stopped human trafficking.

12:46.432 --> 12:48.301
Every time I bought one
of these garments on me,

12:48.301 --> 12:50.303
somebody in need got a pair.

12:50.303 --> 12:52.038
That's the double bottom line.

12:52.038 --> 12:54.240
$1 billion is the grade.

12:54.240 --> 12:55.508
They got an "A"
on their report card

12:55.508 --> 12:57.543
and everybody else
should copy them.

12:57.543 --> 12:59.679
And that's what
Bombas wants people to do.

12:59.679 --> 13:01.547
I'm so proud to be part
of everything you're doing.

13:01.547 --> 13:05.251
I always say that every single
thing in this world

13:05.251 --> 13:07.420
started with one person
that had one idea

13:07.420 --> 13:09.622
that took one action,
and Dave and Randy

13:09.622 --> 13:12.325
and the entire Bombas community
shows it.

13:12.325 --> 13:13.426
John: How you doing, man?
Man: Hey, man.

13:13.426 --> 13:14.494
What's happening?
How you doing?

13:14.494 --> 13:17.330
You know if you buy
one pair of socks,

13:17.330 --> 13:19.132
you've helped one other person.

13:19.132 --> 13:21.267
If everybody did one thing,

13:21.267 --> 13:24.103
an act of kindness
like that in this world,

13:24.103 --> 13:25.338
think about
where we would be.

13:25.338 --> 13:26.539
Pretty amazing.

13:26.539 --> 13:29.308
The impact that we're having
is beyond our wildest dreams.

13:29.308 --> 13:30.476
And it's just
motivating us

13:30.476 --> 13:33.246
to continue to do something
really good for the world.

13:33.246 --> 13:34.247
Nice to meet you.

13:34.247 --> 13:35.281
This company was built

13:35.281 --> 13:36.516
around a single idea --

13:36.516 --> 13:39.452
That a company can exist
to serve its community.

13:39.452 --> 13:40.687
And that's what we're
gonna continue to do

13:40.687 --> 13:44.057
as we build Bombas
for the next generation.

13:44.057 --> 13:46.959
[ Cheers and applause ]

13:54.334 --> 13:56.602
♪♪

13:56.602 --> 13:59.205
Narrator: Next up
is an Earth-friendly option

13:59.205 --> 14:02.175
for one of life's
big milestones.

14:02.175 --> 14:08.614
♪♪

14:08.614 --> 14:12.352
Hi, I'm Micah from
Seattle, Washington.

14:12.352 --> 14:14.854
And I am the CEO
and founder of Return Home.

14:14.854 --> 14:18.391
And I'm Katey, Return Home's
licensed funeral director.

14:18.391 --> 14:21.527
Sharks, families of
the 3.4 million Americans

14:21.527 --> 14:24.330
that die each year
must choose between

14:24.330 --> 14:26.299
two really unsustainable
options --

14:26.299 --> 14:27.800
cremation and burial.

14:27.800 --> 14:32.438
Cremation is just plain
terrible for the earth.

14:32.438 --> 14:34.340
Each year
in the United States,

14:34.340 --> 14:37.210
the cremation industry
burns enough fuel

14:37.210 --> 14:38.644
to send a person
from the earth

14:38.644 --> 14:42.648
to the moon and back
1,300 times.

14:42.648 --> 14:44.550
And caskets
are so wasteful

14:44.550 --> 14:46.252
that we could build
a Golden Gate bridge

14:46.252 --> 14:48.287
each year from
the steel we bury.

14:48.287 --> 14:49.655
As a licensed
funeral director,

14:49.655 --> 14:51.457
I know the methods
we use are toxic

14:51.457 --> 14:54.427
to both our planet
and to our workers.

14:54.427 --> 14:57.663
The way we are dying
is killing us.

14:57.663 --> 15:00.733
The Earth needs
an alternative now.

15:00.733 --> 15:04.570
And that is what we at
Return Home have created.

15:04.570 --> 15:07.373
Our process,
which we call Terramation,

15:07.373 --> 15:10.510
gently transforms
human remains into soil

15:10.510 --> 15:12.645
in just 60 to 90 days.

15:12.645 --> 15:16.716
Rather than pollute the earth,
air, and water when we die,

15:16.716 --> 15:20.319
Terramation ensures our
last act on this planet

15:20.319 --> 15:22.488
is to give back to it.

15:22.488 --> 15:23.856
When the process
is complete,

15:23.856 --> 15:26.759
our families are left with
beautiful life-giving soil

15:26.759 --> 15:29.295
that can be returned
back to the earth,

15:29.295 --> 15:30.730
restarting
the cycle of life.

15:30.730 --> 15:32.498
The Terramated remains
are returned home

15:32.498 --> 15:35.501
to the family or scattered
at our eight-acre woodland,

15:35.501 --> 15:36.669
restarting
nature's cycle

15:36.669 --> 15:38.571
and paying the gift of life
forward.

15:38.571 --> 15:41.274
Sharks, the time is now.

15:41.274 --> 15:45.311
For $2 million and 5%,

15:45.311 --> 15:46.546
we would love
for you to join us

15:46.546 --> 15:49.315
to help revolutionize
global death care

15:49.315 --> 15:52.285
and help millions
return home.

15:52.285 --> 15:53.486
Tell us
about the company.

15:53.486 --> 15:55.421
Katey, why don't we try
process first.

15:55.421 --> 15:56.456
Yeah.
And we go from there.

15:56.456 --> 15:58.357
So people are placed
in a vessel

15:58.357 --> 15:59.559
that looks
just like this.

15:59.559 --> 16:01.360
You go into that
vessel with straw,

16:01.360 --> 16:02.762
alfalfa, and sawdust,

16:02.762 --> 16:05.431
and it's just the amazing
microbes in our body

16:05.431 --> 16:06.866
that transform us
into soil.

16:06.866 --> 16:08.734
So this vessel sits
in our front of house,

16:08.734 --> 16:11.337
which is pictured here
30 to 40 days

16:11.337 --> 16:12.538
while it
transforms into soil.

16:12.538 --> 16:14.574
And then the compost
has to rest

16:14.574 --> 16:16.776
for a further 30 days before
it's ready to return home.

16:16.776 --> 16:19.445
Greiner: Let's say you have
40 bodies, right?

16:19.445 --> 16:20.713
Where do you
put all those?

16:20.713 --> 16:23.449
Like, those vessels take up
a lot of room, don't they?

16:23.449 --> 16:24.717
Yeah, we have
74 vessels total.

16:24.717 --> 16:27.687
Wow.
Which means, we can
take 74 people per month.

16:27.687 --> 16:30.623
Oh, my gosh.
And we have
a 12,000-foot warehouse.

16:30.623 --> 16:31.824
That's where all
of our vessels are.

16:31.824 --> 16:34.427
They're open, doors that
open so families

16:34.427 --> 16:35.628
can come
and visit their vessel.

16:35.628 --> 16:38.231
Can I just start with
an overview of industry?

16:38.231 --> 16:38.798
Sure.

16:38.798 --> 16:41.500
So, 3.4 million
people die

16:41.500 --> 16:43.669
in the United States
every year.

16:43.669 --> 16:47.240
Cremation is skyrocketing.
Believe it's about 57% now.

16:47.240 --> 16:47.840
Let's round up.

16:47.840 --> 16:50.977
About 2 million people
are getting cremated.

16:50.977 --> 16:57.516
Pricing -- $7,000 for a
cremation with matching funeral.

16:57.516 --> 17:01.454
With burial,
burial and funeral -- $8,000,

17:01.454 --> 17:03.522
does not include plot.

17:03.522 --> 17:06.259
Our price, including
our service at our facility,

17:06.259 --> 17:07.860
$5,500.

17:07.860 --> 17:09.362
Cuban: Is there any
competition?

17:09.362 --> 17:10.363
Yes, there are.

17:10.363 --> 17:11.397
There are three companies

17:11.397 --> 17:13.633
currently in
Washington State.

17:13.633 --> 17:15.601
We are one.
There are two others.

17:15.601 --> 17:16.836
Ours is utterly unique

17:16.836 --> 17:19.839
in that our technology developed
allows our families

17:19.839 --> 17:22.909
to take part and be next
to the process throughout.

17:22.909 --> 17:26.512
What we allow is an experience
that no one has seen.

17:26.512 --> 17:28.548
How did you
get to doing this?

17:28.548 --> 17:30.483
I think Katey
should go first.

17:30.483 --> 17:31.684
Katey, go first.
She's more interesting.

17:31.684 --> 17:33.653
I was born and raised
in England.

17:33.653 --> 17:35.621
I moved to the United States
at 18.

17:35.621 --> 17:38.591
I started being a funeral
director in England at age 16.

17:38.591 --> 17:40.459
I went to
my grandfather's funeral,

17:40.459 --> 17:41.694
and while it
was average,

17:41.694 --> 17:43.896
it was not something
that represented him well.

17:43.896 --> 17:46.332
And I decided I could
probably do a better job.

17:46.332 --> 17:47.600
And I have.

17:47.600 --> 17:50.436
I have something in me
that allows me

17:50.436 --> 17:51.637
to take care
of a two-year-old

17:51.637 --> 17:53.005
for that mother
after she passes away

17:53.005 --> 17:56.876
or take care of that husband
who never got to come home.

17:56.876 --> 17:59.312
Funeral directing has
completely changed my life,

17:59.312 --> 17:59.912
and it is something

17:59.912 --> 18:02.481
I hopefully will do
for a long time.

18:02.481 --> 18:03.683
So you have
a lot of empathy.

18:03.683 --> 18:05.217
Right?
Yes.

18:05.217 --> 18:05.718
And you?

18:05.718 --> 18:08.654
After college,
went to China.

18:08.654 --> 18:10.556
There I both worked,

18:10.556 --> 18:11.991
at one point,
I was running The Knot.

18:11.991 --> 18:13.960
You were running
The Knot?
China. China.

18:13.960 --> 18:16.662
Okay.
So, yeah, 20 years
of my life in China.

18:16.662 --> 18:17.863
Moved back
to the States

18:17.863 --> 18:21.500
and was trying to figure out
the thing I needed to do.

18:21.500 --> 18:23.569
So you went from
the wedding business

18:23.569 --> 18:25.805
to the human composting
business?

18:25.805 --> 18:27.773
I wanted
to build a company,

18:27.773 --> 18:29.642
no kidding,
that the bigger it got,

18:29.642 --> 18:31.043
the better off
the world was for it.

18:31.043 --> 18:33.813
Okay.
And it was for that reason
that I made that pivot,

18:33.813 --> 18:35.948
put the teams together,
built the science, technology.

18:35.948 --> 18:37.616
And here we stand
in front of you.

18:37.616 --> 18:39.819
I like it.
But this is your moment.

18:39.819 --> 18:42.321
You're on
the "Shark Tank" carpet.

18:42.321 --> 18:43.656
5% of a business,

18:43.656 --> 18:45.558
and I have to give you
$2 million to get it.
Yes.

18:45.558 --> 18:47.660
It imputes a $40 million
valuation.

18:47.660 --> 18:48.794
It's not proprietary.

18:48.794 --> 18:51.630
I could do it if I had
some sawdust and a box.

18:51.630 --> 18:54.600
Yes.
I got it,
but I need to understand

18:54.600 --> 18:56.435
why you're worth
$40 million.

18:56.435 --> 18:57.770
Sure.
What are your sales?

18:57.770 --> 19:01.607
We did $350,000
last year.

19:01.607 --> 19:04.877
We have already
matched $350,000,

19:04.877 --> 19:08.714
I think, as the end of May,
and continuing to grow.

19:08.714 --> 19:09.915
How much did you
make off the $350,000?

19:09.915 --> 19:11.784
We are a money-losing
company.

19:11.784 --> 19:13.853
Oh, good!
Oh, my goodness.
[ Chuckles ]

19:13.853 --> 19:15.855
So wait, how much money
have you raised

19:15.855 --> 19:17.890
and at what valuation?

19:17.890 --> 19:21.660
We raised at a total
of almost $5 million.

19:21.660 --> 19:22.695
Whoo.

19:22.695 --> 19:24.797
What was the last
valuation you raised at?

19:24.797 --> 19:26.666
$20.6 million.

19:26.666 --> 19:27.666
When was that?

19:27.666 --> 19:28.901
About a year ago.

19:28.901 --> 19:31.537
Wow.
O'Leary: Okay. Why did you
double the valuation

19:31.537 --> 19:32.905
from the last raise?

19:32.905 --> 19:35.541
Yeah.
What's changed that
would make you think

19:35.541 --> 19:36.642
you could come in here
and say,

19:36.642 --> 19:38.010
"It's not worth $21 million
anymore,

19:38.010 --> 19:40.579
it's worth $40 million"?
He's gonna negotiate.

19:40.579 --> 19:42.682
A lot.

19:42.682 --> 19:44.483
Micah,
this is your moment!

19:44.483 --> 19:45.818
Go, go, go!

19:45.818 --> 19:47.086
Let's go,
2 million bucks.

19:47.086 --> 19:50.756
Funeral homes are the worst
marketers in the world.

19:50.756 --> 19:53.826
This is not about land grab.
It's about brand grab.

19:53.826 --> 19:56.696
Tell me, guys,
how many funeral homes

19:56.696 --> 19:58.564
do you know that are amazing
that are cross-country?

19:58.564 --> 20:00.433
Oh, Micah, you blew it.
I'm out.

20:02.668 --> 20:04.937
Greiner: I mean, honestly,
I want to understand

20:04.937 --> 20:07.673
why I should give you
$2 million for 5%.

20:07.673 --> 20:08.974
Why are you worth that?
Sure.

20:08.974 --> 20:11.744
Because you have done
nothing to show me

20:11.744 --> 20:13.746
that your sales
are anywhere near that.

20:13.746 --> 20:15.981
I'd like you to walk us
through the unit profitability.

20:15.981 --> 20:18.084
What are your margins?
$3,800.

20:18.084 --> 20:20.820
Including --
So it costs about $1,200
to transform a body.

20:20.820 --> 20:22.888
We can transform
70 bodies a month.

20:22.888 --> 20:25.157
We are break even
at 23, right?

20:25.157 --> 20:28.027
But are you saying that
the reason you acquire customers

20:28.027 --> 20:31.764
is that it's cheaper
or is it better?

20:31.764 --> 20:32.932
Because you have
to make your decision.

20:32.932 --> 20:34.066
Because I'm looking
at it --

20:34.066 --> 20:35.801
This is not a money-driven
decision on the family's part.

20:35.801 --> 20:37.837
Well, then why not charge
the $8,000 that the burials do

20:37.837 --> 20:39.105
except there's a better
burial strategy?

20:39.105 --> 20:41.907
Well, because actually,
we want to make sure

20:41.907 --> 20:44.910
it's as ubiquitous
and reachable as possible.

20:44.910 --> 20:47.680
I was hoping that there
was more definition

20:47.680 --> 20:48.881
of the business model.
Sure.

20:48.881 --> 20:50.816
Because I like the deal, okay?
I like what you're doing.

20:50.816 --> 20:53.152
Thank you.
But I'm not confident yet

20:53.152 --> 20:55.788
that you have found
the business model.

20:55.788 --> 20:58.591
Look, this is a better way
to be put to rest.

20:58.591 --> 20:59.792
I totally agree.

20:59.792 --> 21:01.127
It's a great innovation...

21:01.127 --> 21:02.661
Uh-huh.
...in terms
of sustainability,

21:02.661 --> 21:03.829
That's the message.

21:03.829 --> 21:06.232
But you gave up
30% of your margin.

21:06.232 --> 21:08.033
Go higher.
But if everybody's
willing to pay $8,000,

21:08.033 --> 21:09.935
you're giving
a discount death. Why?
Sure.

21:09.935 --> 21:11.704
There's no reason.
I'm out.

21:11.704 --> 21:13.072
I got it.
Daniel.

21:13.072 --> 21:18.644
I-I could actually see myself
accepting your valuation,

21:18.644 --> 21:19.945
but only
if I close my eyes

21:19.945 --> 21:22.448
and kept them shut
with Krazy Glue.

21:22.448 --> 21:23.849
[ Laughter ]

21:23.849 --> 21:27.453
Your valuation makes no sense.
I'm out.

21:28.788 --> 21:30.122
John: First of all,
I have a massive respect

21:30.122 --> 21:32.124
about people like you
who deal with the --

21:32.124 --> 21:35.060
with the more
challenging aspects in life.

21:35.060 --> 21:37.930
And I've lost a lot of people in
my life, so I do respect that.

21:37.930 --> 21:40.533
But I have to be
passionate about

21:40.533 --> 21:41.767
everything I invest in,

21:41.767 --> 21:44.603
and I am not passionate
about this, so I'm out.

21:44.603 --> 21:45.704
Yep.

21:46.906 --> 21:50.876
So I did Parting Stone
last year, a deal with Kevin.

21:50.876 --> 21:52.077
It's phenomenal.

21:52.077 --> 21:54.847
Take the ashes, you turn it
to a beautiful stone.

21:54.847 --> 21:58.050
It's less expensive
than all of this and...

21:58.050 --> 21:59.051
O'Leary:
Absolutely.

21:59.051 --> 22:01.053
I feel that the valuation

22:01.053 --> 22:02.822
is a real stumbling block

22:02.822 --> 22:05.824
because I need proof,
concrete proof.

22:05.824 --> 22:07.826
And I really look at this

22:07.826 --> 22:10.863
and I feel like you need
valuation evaluation.

22:10.863 --> 22:11.864
Got it.

22:11.864 --> 22:12.865
I'm out.

22:12.865 --> 22:14.066
Thank you, guys.

22:14.066 --> 22:15.568
John: Thank you.
Lubetzky: Thank you,
guys. Good luck.

22:15.568 --> 22:16.068
Good luck, guys.

22:16.068 --> 22:17.069
We really
appreciate you.

22:17.069 --> 22:18.704
And thank you
for what you do.

22:18.704 --> 22:20.272
♪♪

22:20.272 --> 22:22.675
Truman: The Sharks were
really tough on valuation.

22:22.675 --> 22:23.909
I was high on valuation.

22:23.909 --> 22:26.111
It got into a snarl
on that side,

22:26.111 --> 22:28.080
wanted very much
to talk mission,

22:28.080 --> 22:30.216
why it matters, why it changes
the world so much.

22:30.216 --> 22:32.985
But obviously that was
a hard one to shake

22:32.985 --> 22:35.821
and the Sharks were not
ultimately interested.

22:35.821 --> 22:37.223
Narrator:
For our milestone 15th season,

22:37.223 --> 22:39.959
we're counting down the top
15 "Shark Tank" companies

22:39.959 --> 22:42.094
with the highest total
retail sales.

22:42.094 --> 22:46.265
Number 12 is CordaRoy's
with $195 million.

22:46.265 --> 22:50.102
Number 11 is PRx Performance
with $200 million.

22:50.102 --> 22:53.772
And number 10 is Squatty Potty
with $260 million

22:53.772 --> 22:55.007
